<chapter>
<title>Tips and Tricks</title>
<section>  
<body>

  <p><b>Protecting files with noclobber</b></p>

  <p>This tip is for people who have ever hosed important files by using &gt;
    when they meant to use &gt;&gt;. Add the following line to
    <path>.bashrc</path>: <c>set -o noclobber</c>. The noclobber
    option prevents you from overwriting existing files with the &gt;
    operator.</p>

  <pre>
% <i>program &gt; file2</i>
bash: file2: cannot overwrite existing file</pre>

  <p>In some cases you may really want to overwrite the file. In this
    case, instead of turning noclobber off, you can use <c>&gt;|</c>
    to force the file to be written.</p>

  <pre>
% <i>program &gt;| file2 </i></pre>

</body>
</section>
